{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e81de473-1844-43a2-b1b2-7f52c9ec7884","content":"**The problem:** In ASP.NET Core, a \"scope\" = one HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no equivalent automatic scope boundary — the app effectively has one long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your DbContext lives for the entire app lifetime, accumulating tracked entities across navigations.\n\n**Fixes (pick one):**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — new instance each time it's injected.\n\n2. **Create scopes manually** via `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Disable tracking** if you're mostly reading:\n   ```csharp\n   services.AddDbContext<MyDbContext>(o =>\n       o.UseSqlite(\"...\").UseQueryTrackingBehavior(QueryTrackingBehavior.NoTracking));\n   ```\n\n`AddTransient` is the simplest drop-in fix for most MAUI apps.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"af93e879-76cf-46ff-8fae-6b25d0de464c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common issue when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping behavior. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request — the app has a single long-lived scope (essentially the app lifetime), so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`. This means the DbContext is never disposed/recreated between page navigations, causing data to persist in the change tracker.","outputTokens":430,"requestId":"9814:23E21D:16A52ED:1947B2B:6A0520C0"},"id":"863edce6-626a-4962-8e9a-e119e4066631","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:09:30.017Z","parentId":"6a4b330d-a8cb-475d-bbe1-c4eca697f9e5"}
